examples of open sets are provided using intervals on the real number line. The video demonstrates why open intervals, such as (a,b), perfectly fit the definition of an open set. It explains how any point within these intervals can always have a sufficiently small epsilon-neighborhood that remains completely inside the interval, illustrating the concept practically.\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"title\": \"Key Properties of Open Sets\",\n            \"timestamp\": \"00:10:00\",\n            \"summary\": \"This subsection outlines the essential properties that characterize open sets in topological spaces. It explains that the union of any collection of open sets is always an open set. Additionally, it highlights that the intersection of a *finite* number of open sets also results in an open set. These properties are fundamental theorems in topology and real analysis.\"\n          }\n        ]\n      },\n      {\n        \"title\": \"Closed Sets and Their Relationship with Open Sets\",\n        \"subsections\": [\n          {\n            \"title\": \"Intuitive Idea and Formal Definition of Closed Sets\",\n            \"timestamp\": \"00:12:30\",\n            \"summary\": \"The lecture introduces the intuitive notion of a closed set as one that 'contains all its boundary points' or 'all its limit points'. It then presents the formal definition of a closed set, which often states that a set is closed if it contains all its limit points. This provides a precise mathematical criterion for identifying closed sets.\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"title\": \"Closed Sets as Complements of Open Sets\",\n            \"timestamp\": \"00:15:00\",\n            \"summary\": \"This section explains a fundamental duality in topology: a set is closed if and only if its complement is open. This powerful relationship provides an alternative and often simpler way to define and identify closed sets. Understanding this complementary nature is key to working with 