rely contained within the set. There are no 'edge' points that belong to the set itself.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Provide the formal definition of an open set in a metric space.\",\n      \"answer\": \"A set S in a metric space is open if for every point x in S, there exists an epsilon (ε > 0) such that the open ball B(x, ε) is entirely contained within S.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is an epsilon-neighborhood?\",\n      \"answer\": \"An epsilon-neighborhood of a point x is an open ball (or open interval on the real line) centered at x with radius epsilon (ε). It includes all points whose distance from x is less than ε.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is an interior point of a set?\",\n      \"answer\": \"An interior point of a set S is a point x in S for which there exists an epsilon-neighborhood centered at x that is completely contained within S. All points of an open set are interior points.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Give an example of an open set on the real number line.\",\n      \"answer\": \"An open interval such as (2, 5) is an open set on the real number line. This includes all real numbers strictly greater than 2 and strictly less than 5, but not the endpoints themselves.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is the intuitive idea of a closed set?\",\n      \"answer\": \"An intuitively closed set is one that 'contains its boundary' or 'contains all its limit points'. If you approach a boundary from within the set, the boundary point itself is part of the set.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Provide the formal definition of a closed set using limit points.\",\n      \"answer\": \"A set S in a metric space is closed if it contains all its limit points (also known as accumulation points). This means if a sequence of points in S converges to a point, that limit point must also be in S.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"How can a closed set be defined in relation to an open set?\",\n      \"answer\": \"A set S is closed if and only if its complement (the set of all points not in S, within the universal space) is an open set. This is a fundamental duality in topology.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Give an example of a closed set on the real number line.\",\n      \"answer\": \"A closed interval such as [2, 5] is a closed set on the real number line. This includes all real numbers greater than or equal to 2 and less than or equal to 5, including both endpoints.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Can a set be both open and closed?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Yes, a set can be both open and closed, known as a 'clopen' set. In a connected space, the only clopen sets are typically the empty set and the entire space itself.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Provide an example of a set that is both open and closed.\",\n      \"answer\": \"In the standard real number line R, the empty set (Ø) and the set of all real numbers (R) are both considered open and closed sets. They are called clopen sets.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Can a set be neither open nor closed?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Yes, many sets are neither open nor closed. These sets typically include some, but not all, of their boundary points.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Give an example of a set that is neither open nor closed on the real line.\",\n      \"answer\": \"A half-open or half-closed interval, such as (2, 5], is neither open nor closed. It contains one endpoint (5) but not the other (2), violating both definitions fully.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Is the empty set (Ø) an open set?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Yes, the empty set is considered an open set. This is because the condition for an open set (for every point in the set, an epsilon-neighborhood exists within the set) is vacuously true since there are no points in the empty set.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Is the empty set (Ø) a closed set?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Yes, the empty set is considered a closed set. This is because its complement, which is the entire space (e.g., R), is an open set. Alternatively, it contains all its limit points, vacuously.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is the property of the union of open sets?\",\n      \"answer\": \"The union of any collection (finite or infinite) of open sets is always an open set. This means if you combine any number of open sets, the resulting set will also be open.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is the property of the intersection of open sets?\",\n      \"answer\": \"The intersection of a *finite* number of open sets is an open set. However, the intersection of an infinite number of open sets is not necessarily open.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is the property of the union of closed sets?\",\n      \"answer\": \"The union of a *finite* number of closed sets is a closed set. However, the union of an infinite number of closed sets is not necessarily closed.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is the property of the intersection of closed sets?\",\n      \"answer\": \"The intersection of any collection (finite or infinite) of closed sets is always a closed set. This means if you find the common elements of any number of closed sets, the result will also be closed.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"In the context of the real line (R), is the set of rational numbers (Q) open or closed?\",\n      \"answer\": \"The set of rational numbers (Q) is neither open nor closed in R. It's not open because any epsilon-neighborhood around a rational number will contain irrational numbers. It's not closed because its complement (irrationals) is not open, and it doesn't contain all its limit points (every real number is a limit point of Q).\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```"
